              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a lively 5-year-old girl from Prague, Czech Republic, who attends kindergarten and loves drawing, playing with her dolls, and dancing to children's songs. She lives with her parents and her 8-year-old brother in a cosy flat in a residential neighbourhood. Her mother brought her to the paediatric outpatient clinic this morning after {patientName} spent a restless night waking repeatedly with fever and complaints of a very sore throat [MEDDIALOG:J03.9:7]. She was tearful and reluctant to eat her breakfast because swallowing was painful [MEDLINEPLUS:J03.9].\n\nOn examination {patientName} appears flushed and tired, with watery eyes and flushed cheeks. She is cooperative but clearly uncomfortable. Her voice sounds slightly muffled and she keeps touching her neck. Oral inspection reveals markedly red, swollen tonsils with mild exudate, consistent with acute tonsillitis [SNOMED:J03.9, MEDLINEPLUS:J03.9]. Her mother also mentions that {patientName} complained of stomach pain during the night, a common accompanying complaint in young children with tonsillitis [MEDDIALOG:J03.9:7].\n\n{patientName} enjoys outdoor play at the kindergarten playground and participates in a weekend gymnastics group. She has a good appetite under normal circumstances and is a generally healthy child who socialises well with peers. Her parents are both employed — her father as a civil engineer and her mother as a primary-school teacher. The family has no pets and lives in a smoke-free household."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:bbf4e81f-ace0-42bc-ac38-68519c84d3fe",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
